Which, in words at length, is, The square of the velocity of the wheel, multiplied by the whole force, pressure, or head of the water, and divided by the square of the velocity of the wa|ter, quotes the pressure, force or head of water, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">hat is left unbalanced by the load, to produce the velocity of the wheel, which pressure, force or head, subtracted from the whole pressure, force <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> head, leaves the load that is on the wheel.</P>
</DIV5>
<DIV5 TYPE="theorem">
<PB N="74" REF="028644_0082_0FDA2A6A21853510">
<HEAD>Art. 42. Theorem for finding the Velocity of the Wheel, when we have the Velocity of the Water, Load at Equi|librio, and Load on the Wheel given.</HEAD>
<P>As the square root of the whole pressure, force or load at equilibrio, is to the velocity of the water, so is the square root of the difference, be|tween the load on the wheel, and the load at equilibrio, to the velocity of the wheel.</P>
</DIV5>
<DIV5 TYPE="problem">
<HEAD>PROBLEM.</HEAD>
<P>Let V=velocity of the water-32,4,<LB>
P=pressure, force, head, or load at equili|brio=16,<LB>
l=the load on the wheel, suppose 12,<LB>
v=velocity of the wheel,<LB>
Then by the<LB>
Theorem &radic;P:V::&radic;P&mdash;l:v<LB>
